{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T10:00:30Z", "url": "https://gnomestew.com/gnomecast-212-problem-players/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T10:00:30Z", "content": "Written by a team of veteran Gamers and Gamemasters, Gnome Stew is a widely read gaming blog with multiple awards, ennies, and thousands of articles. We’re dedicated to helping gamers have more fun a… [+18 chars]", "title": "Gnomecast 212 – Problem Players", "fullContent": "https://polygamero.us/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/GC_212_Problemplayers_final.mp3 Join Ang and Jared, along with special guest Carl Lehmann as they talk about problem players and what to do about them when you find one at your table. Links: Origins Game Faire Fury of the Forsaken by Lou Anders Symphony Entertainment\n\nJoin Ang and Jared, along with special guest Carl Lehmann as they talk about problem players and what to do about them when you find one at your table.\n\nThis post is brought to you by our wonderful patron Doug Raas , supporting us since July 2018 ! Thanks for helping us keep the stew fires going!"}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T04:01:00Z", "url": "http://digiday.com/media/from-hype-to-reality-ai-in-publishing-by-the-numbers/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T04:01:00Z", "content": "Its been a year since Google rolled out AI Overviews, and over two years since the launches of ChatGPT and Perplexity tools that have collectively upended the traditional relationship between publish… [+6931 chars]", "title": "From hype to reality: AI in publishing — by the numbers", "fullContent": "As a Digiday+ member, you were able to access this article early through the Digiday+ Story Preview email. See other exclusives or manage your account .This article was provided as an exclusive preview for Digiday+ members, who were able to access it early. Check out the other features included with Digiday+ to help you stay ahead\n\nIt’s been a year since Google rolled out AI Overviews, and over two years since the launches of ChatGPT and Perplexity — tools that have collectively upended the traditional relationship between publishers, platforms and audiences.\n\nThe spread of AI technology is having an increasingly clear impact on publishers’ traffic and their ability to control content scraping.\n\nDigiday has sifted through the data to find the numbers that help show where publishers stand now when it comes to AI. Here’s what you need to know:\n\nThe steady chipping away of traffic\n\nAI bots are driving dramatically less traffic to publishers than traditional Google search — 95.7% less on average, according to a report published in February by Tollbit, an analytics and licensing platform for publishers and AI companies.\n\nWhile AI search engines refer users back to publishers 0.74% of the time per content scrape — better than chatbots, which refer users to publishers at a rate of just 0.33% — they still generate 91% fewer referrals than the average clickthrough rate from the top 100 organic Google search results, per the Tollbit report.\n\nNaturally, chatbot traffic (from tools like ChatGPT or Perplexity) is relatively small and experimental in scale. While chatbots do matter, publishers are currently more concerned about how Google’s AI Overviews might replace or dilute traditional search traffic, on which they rely heavily.\n\nA Semrush study published this week analyzing over 10 million keywords found that Google is showing more AI Overviews in search results. Over 13% of all search queries triggered AI Overviews in March 2025, up from 6.49% in January 2025. The science, health, and people and society industries experienced the largest share growth of AI Overviews (up about 20%) from January to March, likely due to the “high-trust, information dense” nature of these categories, according to the report.\n\nMeanwhile, software company Ahrefs analyzed 300,000 keywords and found that Google AI Overviews in search results correlated with a 34.5% lower average CTR for the top-ranking page, compared to similar keywords without an AI Overview. (This is how some are calculating AI Overviews’ impact, as there is still no way to separate Google AI Overviews clicks and impressions from the results of publishers’ Google search data.)\n\nEven when AI chatbots and search engines do cite their sources, the links in which they do so don’t always work to drive a user to those pages. A Tow Center for Digital Journalism report found that more than half of responses from Google’s Gemini and Grok 3 cited fabricated or broken URLs that led to error pages.\n\nGenerative AI in the Newsroom, a project from Northwestern University, also found that sites in the news publisher category only received 3.2% of ChatGPT’s filtered traffic and 7.4% of Perplexity’s filtered traffic in March 2025. Only 5 out of 143 news sites in the study’s sample received 100 or more unique visitors from ChatGPT and Perplexity from July to November 2024.\n\nAI bot scraping is getting worse\n\nAI crawlers are continuing to scrape publishers’ web content for free — and the situation is getting worse.\n\nScrapes per website doubled from Q3 to Q4 in 2024, and scrapes per page more than tripled in that time, according to Tollbit’s report. The top scrapers per page in Q4 were from ChatGPT, Meta and Perplexity.\n\nPublishers who don’t want AI bots scraping their sites for content to train tech companies’ large language models can use robots.txt — a few lines of code that tell web crawlers which URLs they can access — to disallow access to their sites.\n\nBut that mechanism isn’t working all that well. AI bot scrapes bypassing robots.txt grew by over 40% between Q3 and Q4 2024, according to Tollbit’s report.\n\nAI bot scraping activity increased significantly between Q3 and Q4 2024 for a cohort of websites “with constant bot-blocking strategies,” according to the report. Average scrapes per website for that cohort rose from 3.13 million in Q3 to 5.05 million in Q4, an increase of more than 61%. AI bot traffic as a percentage of total traffic grew by 117% between Q3 and Q4 2024 for those sites. For all sites Tollbit measured in Q4, 3.3% of scrapes bypassed robots.txt.\n\nThe largest share of AI bot traffic compared to total AI traffic was coming from OpenAI, TikTok and Meta, per Tollbit.\n\nLawsuit revelations\n\nLawsuits by publishers like The New York Times and Ziff Davis shed some light on the level of AI bot scraping, despite publishers’ efforts to block those bots.\n\nZiff Davis’ lawsuit claims that its domains “accounted for 168,091 documents within the 19 million web pages from the top 1,000 domains in WebText,” which is the training dataset for OpenAI’s large language model GPT-2.\n\nZiff Davis also claims that OpenAI training datasets contain over one million Ziff Davis articles.\n\nMeanwhile, The New York Times’ lawsuit alleges that NYTimes.com is the fifth top domain in the WebText dataset, with 333,160 entries. Times content accounts for 1.23% of all sources listed in OpenWebText2, with a total of 209,707 unique URLs.\n\nAnd to add insult to injury, publishers may be facing a new blow: Google can still use publishers’ content to train its search-related AI features — like AI Overviews — even if those publishers have opted out of AI training, a Google executive testified at the platform’s antitrust trial hearing on May 3, according to Bloomberg.\n\nAI deals start to show glimmers of returns\n\nPublishers who have signed deals with AI tech companies are seeing increases in referral traffic from AI search engines and chatbots — but data shows the traffic isn’t all that significant.\n\nFor example, referrals from ChatGPT to The Atlantic’s site rose by more than 80% from December to January, according to Digiday reporting. The Atlantic signed a deal with OpenAI in May 2024.\n\nHowever, the Generative AI in Newsroom report found that OpenAI’s partner sites don’t receive significantly more traffic than non-partners. Partner sites averaged 18 additional visitors from July to November 2024 — and while that was double the number of visitors compared with non-partner sites, the difference wasn’t significant.\n\nChartbeat data shared with Digiday shows referrals from ChatGPT are growing. Across more than 3,700 news and non-news publishers, page views from ChatGPT increased from 363,000 in August 2024 to 3 million in January 2025. In April, that number jumped to 5.3 million page views. But that comes out to only about 1,400 page views per publisher.\n\nPage views from Perplexity have grown from about 306,000 in August 2024 to 693,000 in April 2025, according to Chartbeat — which comes out to about 187 page views per publisher.\n\nIndependent publishers will be the first casualties of AI\n\nA number of independent publishers have reportedly seen their website traffic tank since the expansion of AI bots, search engines and chatbots — especially since the rollout of Google’s AI Overviews.\n\nWorld History Encyclopedia — the world’s second-most visited history website — saw traffic drop 25% in November after appearing in AI Overviews, CEO Jan van der Crabben told Big Technology.\n\nAbout 25 independent publishers told Bloomberg that they had seen traffic plummet as a result of AI Overviews, with one website owner reportedly seeing traffic from Google fall more than 70% following AI Overviews’ rollout."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T07:19:59Z", "url": "https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/no-code-web-app-development-tools/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T07:19:59Z", "content": "What if you could turn your automation workflows into fully functional web applications without writing a single line of code? Imagine creating a sleek, client-ready app that automates repetitive tas… [+8234 chars]", "title": "Easily Convert n8n AI Workflows into Stunning Web Apps (No Code)", "fullContent": "\n\nWhat if you could turn your automation workflows into fully functional web applications without writing a single line of code? Imagine creating a sleek, client-ready app that automates repetitive tasks, manages data securely, and scales effortlessly—all using tools you already know, like n8n, Supabase, and Lovable. The rise of no-code platforms has made this not just possible but practical, empowering creators and businesses to build solutions that were once the domain of seasoned developers. But here’s the catch: while these tools are powerful on their own, combining them strategically is the real fantastic option. This exploration dives into how you can bridge the gap between automation workflows and full-fledged web apps, unlocking new possibilities for innovation and efficiency.\n\nIn the following guide, AI Automators shows how to architect your application, integrate modular workflows, and use the strengths of platforms like n8n for seamless automation. You’ll learn how to design intuitive frontends, secure sensitive data, and scale your app to meet evolving client needs. Whether you’re building a multi-instance app for tailored client experiences or a multi-tenant solution for cost-effective scaling, this guide will equip you with the tools and insights to make it happen. By the end, you won’t just understand how to package your workflows—you’ll see how to transform them into scalable, adaptable web applications that stand out in a crowded digital landscape. After all, the future of app development isn’t just about what you build; it’s about how you bring it to life.\n\nBuilding No-Code Web Apps\n\nTL;DR Key Takeaways : No-code platforms like Lovable, Supabase, and n8n enable users to build scalable, client-branded web applications without advanced programming skills by integrating automation workflows and addressing unique client needs.\n\nApplication architecture choices, such as multi-instance or multi-tenant setups, significantly impact scalability, data isolation, and resource management, with multi-tenant setups requiring robust data separation mechanisms.\n\nKey workflows for no-code applications include content generation, image creation, and automated publishing, with tools like Supabase managing backend operations and n8n automating repetitive tasks.\n\nSecurity best practices, such as using Supabase secrets for API keys and implementing authorization tokens, are essential to protect sensitive data and ensure application integrity.\n\nScalability and modularity are critical for long-term success, allowing seamless integration of advanced features like image regeneration, social media sharing, and customizable workflows to meet evolving client demands.\n\nUsing No-Code Tools for Workflow Integration\n\nCreating a robust web application often involves combining the unique strengths of multiple no-code platforms. Each tool contributes a specific functionality essential for the development process:\n\nLovable: A front-end development platform that enables the design of intuitive and user-friendly interfaces.\n\nA front-end development platform that enables the design of intuitive and user-friendly interfaces. Supabase: A backend service that manages user authentication, database operations, and secure storage of sensitive data such as API keys.\n\nA backend service that manages user authentication, database operations, and secure storage of sensitive data such as API keys. n8n: An automation tool that simplifies repetitive tasks like content generation, image creation, and publishing workflows.\n\nBy integrating these platforms, you can create a seamless, efficient experience for users while automating complex processes. This approach not only saves time but also ensures that your application remains adaptable to evolving client needs.\n\nDesigning Your Application Architecture\n\nA critical step in the development process is deciding on the architecture of your application. The choice between multi-instance and multi-tenant architectures will significantly impact how your app operates and scales:\n\nMulti-Instance Architecture: This approach involves creating a separate application instance for each client. It simplifies data isolation and customization but requires more resources for maintenance and scaling.\n\nThis approach involves creating a separate application instance for each client. It simplifies data isolation and customization but requires more resources for maintenance and scaling. Multi-Tenant Architecture: In this setup, a single application serves multiple clients. While it is more cost-effective, it demands robust mechanisms for data separation to ensure security and privacy.\n\nFor multi-tenant applications, implementing generic webhooks is essential to manage client-specific workflows efficiently. These webhooks allow you to handle client data and tasks dynamically, making sure smooth operations across multiple users.\n\nHow to Convert n8n Workflows into Web Apps\n\nBrowse through more resources below from our in-depth content covering more areas on no-code AI tools.\n\nStep-by-Step Guide to App Development\n\n1. Frontend Design\n\nBegin by designing a user-friendly interface that prioritizes simplicity and functionality. Tools like UX Pilot can assist in creating wireframes and high-fidelity prototypes. Focus on layouts that enable users to easily generate, edit, and publish content. A well-designed interface not only enhances user experience but also reduces the learning curve for your clients, making the application more accessible.\n\n2. Backend Integration\n\nSet up Supabase to handle backend operations, including user authentication and secure storage of sensitive data such as API keys. Use n8n to automate backend workflows, which may include:\n\nGenerating structured article outlines.\n\nCreating images using external APIs.\n\nPublishing content to platforms like WordPress or other CMS tools.\n\nEnsure that these workflows are modular and adaptable, allowing for easy updates or scaling as your application evolves. This modularity will also make it simpler to add new features or address client-specific requirements.\n\nKey Workflow Components\n\nThe core functionality of your application will likely revolve around several key workflows. These workflows form the backbone of your app’s operations:\n\nOutline Creation: Use language models and real-time data to generate detailed and structured article outlines tailored to specific topics.\n\nUse language models and real-time data to generate detailed and structured article outlines tailored to specific topics. Content Generation: Develop complete articles based on predefined prompts, templates, or client-specific requirements.\n\nDevelop complete articles based on predefined prompts, templates, or client-specific requirements. Image Creation: Integrate external APIs to generate relevant visuals that complement the content.\n\nIntegrate external APIs to generate relevant visuals that complement the content. Content Publishing: Automate the process of uploading articles to platforms like WordPress, making sure consistency and efficiency.\n\nTo safeguard sensitive information, use Supabase secrets for managing API keys and webhook integrations. This approach ensures that unauthorized users cannot access critical data, maintaining the security and integrity of your application.\n\nTesting and Debugging\n\nBefore deploying your application, conduct thorough testing of each workflow and webhook. This process helps identify and resolve potential issues, such as JSON parsing errors or UI glitches. Iterative debugging ensures a smoother user experience and minimizes disruptions post-launch. Testing should also include stress tests to evaluate how the application performs under heavy usage, making sure it remains reliable and responsive.\n\nDeployment and Scaling\n\nDeploy your application using Lovable’s built-in tools or custom domains to give your app a professional and polished appearance. Automate client onboarding by streamlining the process of adding new accounts, reducing manual effort and improving efficiency. To enhance security, implement authorization tokens for webhook calls and other sensitive operations.\n\nScalability is a crucial consideration for long-term success. By designing modular workflows and webhooks, you can easily introduce new features—such as image regeneration or social media sharing—without disrupting existing functionality. This flexibility ensures that your application can adapt to the changing needs of your clients.\n\nExtending Your Application’s Functionality\n\nTo differentiate your application and provide additional value to clients, consider incorporating advanced features. These enhancements can improve user experience and expand the app’s capabilities:\n\nEnable image regeneration to allow users to refine visuals for their content.\n\nto allow users to refine visuals for their content. Integrate social media sharing options to help clients expand their content’s reach.\n\noptions to help clients expand their content’s reach. Offer customizable workflows tailored to specific client requirements, providing a more personalized experience.\n\nBy using the modular nature of webhooks, these features can be added seamlessly without requiring significant changes to the app’s core architecture.\n\nBest Practices for Development\n\nTo ensure the success of your application, adhere to these best practices during development:\n\nBreak down complex workflows into smaller, manageable components to simplify debugging and updates.\n\nPrioritize security by avoiding the exposure of sensitive data in front-end code or prompts.\n\nAdopt a product-focused mindset to ensure your app meets the specific needs and expectations of your clients.\n\nThese strategies will help you create a reliable, scalable solution that delivers consistent value to your clients while maintaining high standards of security and usability.\n\nMedia Credit: The AI Automators\n\n\n\nLatest Geeky Gadgets Deals\n\nSome of our articles include affiliate links. If you buy something through one of these links, Geeky Gadgets may earn an affiliate commission. Learn about our Disclosure Policy"}
