{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T11:00:41Z", "url": "https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/samsung-galaxy-z-fold-7-8/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T11:00:41Z", "content": "The Samsung Galaxy Z Fold 7 is poised to redefine the foldable smartphone market. With its new design, enhanced displays, and advanced features, it represents a significant leap in mobile technology.… [+5634 chars]", "title": "Samsung Galaxy Z Fold 7: Brace Yourself for a Major Twist", "fullContent": "The Samsung Galaxy Z Fold 7 is poised to redefine the foldable smartphone market. With its new design, enhanced displays, and advanced features, it represents a significant leap in mobile technology. Whether you are a tech enthusiast or a casual user, this device promises to deliver a premium experience that blends innovation with practicality. Here’s an in-depth look at what makes the Galaxy Z Fold 7 a standout in the foldable smartphone space in a new video from TechTalkTV.\n\nThinner, Sleeker Design\n\nSamsung has carefully engineered the Galaxy Z Fold 7 to be the thinnest foldable phone to date. When folded, it measures an impressive 8.2 mm thick, and when unfolded, it’s just 4.1 mm. This ultra-slim profile not only enhances portability but also improves usability in both folded and unfolded modes. The design reflects Samsung’s dedication to pushing the boundaries of engineering, making sure the device remains both functional and stylish. While minor design adjustments may still occur before its release, this achievement underscores Samsung’s leadership in the foldable market.\n\nEnhanced Display Technology\n\nThe Galaxy Z Fold 7 introduces significant advancements in display technology, offering users a more refined and immersive experience. Key improvements include:\n\nA wider cover screen that provides a more traditional smartphone feel when the device is folded.\n\nReduced crease visibility on both the inner and outer displays, addressing a common concern among foldable device users.\n\nThese upgrades aim to deliver a seamless viewing experience, whether you’re multitasking, streaming your favorite content, or browsing the web. By focusing on these refinements, Samsung ensures that the Galaxy Z Fold 7 caters to both productivity and entertainment needs.\n\nCamera Innovations for Photography Enthusiasts\n\nPhotography enthusiasts will find much to appreciate in the Galaxy Z Fold 7. The device is expected to feature a 200 MP main camera, borrowed from the Galaxy S25 Ultra, which ensures exceptional image quality and detail. Additionally, the under-display selfie camera is set to receive enhancements, offering a more immersive screen experience without compromising photo quality. These advancements make the Galaxy Z Fold 7 a versatile option for users who value high-quality imaging, whether for casual snapshots or professional-grade photography.\n\nS Pen Integration: Productivity Meets Innovation\n\nThe Galaxy Z Fold 7 continues Samsung’s tradition of integrating the S Pen stylus, adding a layer of productivity-focused functionality. However, a notable change is that the stylus will now require charging, even for basic tasks. While this adjustment may raise concerns about convenience, it could also unlock new features that maximize the S Pen’s potential. For users who rely on the stylus for note-taking, sketching, or creative tasks, this update could enhance the overall experience, making the device even more versatile.\n\nSoftware and AI-Driven Enhancements\n\nRunning on Android 16 and paired with Samsung’s One UI 8, the Galaxy Z Fold 7 promises a more intuitive and polished user experience. Samsung is also expected to introduce new AI-powered features designed to:\n\nEnhance multitasking capabilities, allowing users to manage multiple apps seamlessly.\n\nImprove personalization and optimize device performance based on user habits.\n\nThese software advancements aim to position the Galaxy Z Fold 7 as a leader in the Android ecosystem, offering users a device that adapts to their needs while delivering a smooth and efficient experience.\n\nBattery Efficiency and Design Balance\n\nDespite its numerous upgrades, the Galaxy Z Fold 7 is unlikely to feature a larger battery. This decision appears to be driven by the need to maintain its slim and lightweight design. However, Samsung is expected to compensate for this with improved battery efficiency and software optimizations. These enhancements are designed to ensure reliable performance throughout the day, even with heavy usage, making the device practical for everyday use.\n\nFuture Innovations: Trifold Displays and Beyond\n\nSamsung’s commitment to innovation extends beyond the Galaxy Z Fold 7. The company has confirmed development on a trifold Galaxy G Fold, which could debut later this year. This device is expected to feature a innovative three-panel design, further pushing the boundaries of foldable technology. Additionally, the Galaxy Watch 8 Classic, set for release in July, will offer a sleeker design and enhanced functionality, enriching Samsung’s ecosystem of connected devices. These upcoming products highlight Samsung’s vision for the future of mobile technology, making sure it remains at the forefront of the industry.\n\nThe Galaxy Z Fold 7: A Bold Step Forward\n\nThe Samsung Galaxy Z Fold 7 represents a bold step forward in the evolution of foldable smartphones. Its thinner design, improved displays, advanced cameras, and refined software make it a compelling choice for users seeking innovative technology. While the charging requirement for the S Pen and the unchanged battery capacity may spark some debate, the overall package is undeniably impressive. With innovations like the trifold Galaxy G Fold and the Galaxy Watch 8 Classic on the horizon, Samsung continues to shape the future of mobile technology, offering users devices that combine innovation, functionality, and style.\n\nHere are more detailed guides and articles that you may find helpful on Foldable phone.\n\nSource & Image Credit: TechTalkTV\n\n\n\nLatest Geeky Gadgets Deals\n\nSome of our articles include affiliate links. If you buy something through one of these links, Geeky Gadgets may earn an affiliate commission. Learn about our Disclosure Policy"}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T09:00:43Z", "url": "https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/oled-macbook-pro/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T09:00:43Z", "content": "Apple is reportedly preparing to launch a redesigned MacBook Pro featuring OLED display technology by late 2026. This highly anticipated update is expected to deliver a range of enhancements, includi… [+5983 chars]", "title": "OLED MacBook Pro Leaks: Get Ready for a Display Like Never Before!", "fullContent": "Apple is reportedly preparing to launch a redesigned MacBook Pro featuring OLED display technology by late 2026. This highly anticipated update is expected to deliver a range of enhancements, including a sleeker design, improved thermal performance, and potentially a notch-free display. However, these advancements may come with a modest price increase compared to current models, reflecting the integration of innovative components. The video below from Matt Talks Tech gives us more details on what to expect from the OLED MacBook Pro.\n\nThe Advantages of OLED Displays\n\nThe transition to OLED technology represents a significant upgrade for the MacBook Pro, offering several key benefits over the mini-LED displays used in current models. OLED technology is renowned for its ability to deliver superior visual quality and energy efficiency, making it particularly appealing for professionals and everyday users alike. Key advantages include:\n\nEnhanced Color Accuracy: OLED displays provide more precise and vibrant colors, which is especially valuable for creative professionals working in fields like photography, video editing, and graphic design.\n\nOLED displays provide more precise and vibrant colors, which is especially valuable for creative professionals working in fields like photography, video editing, and graphic design. Deeper Contrast Ratios: With the ability to produce true blacks and brighter highlights, OLED technology creates a more immersive and visually striking experience.\n\nWith the ability to produce true blacks and brighter highlights, OLED technology creates a more immersive and visually striking experience. Improved Energy Efficiency: OLED panels consume less power compared to traditional display technologies, potentially extending battery life and making the device more practical for users who rely on long-lasting performance.\n\nApple has already demonstrated the potential of OLED displays in its iPad Pro lineup, showcasing their ability to deliver exceptional visual quality. By bringing this technology to the MacBook Pro, Apple aims to enhance the overall user experience while allowing design improvements such as thinner bezels. These thinner bezels not only create a more immersive screen but also contribute to a modern and streamlined aesthetic.\n\nA Refined and Practical Design\n\nThe upcoming MacBook Pro is rumored to feature a design that is 10-20% thinner than current models. This reduction in thickness strikes a balance between portability and functionality, making the device easier to carry without compromising on essential features. While it may not match the ultra-thin profile of the MacBook Air, the slimmer design will appeal to users who prioritize both performance and convenience.\n\nApple is also expected to retain key ports such as HDMI and SD card slots, making sure the device remains versatile and practical for professionals who require reliable connectivity options. Additionally, one of the most exciting potential updates is the removal of the notch. Apple may introduce under-display Face ID technology or a smaller camera cutout, resulting in a cleaner and more modern look. This aligns with Apple’s ongoing commitment to maximizing screen real estate and minimizing visual distractions.\n\nOptimized Thermal Management for Next-Generation Performance\n\nTo support the slimmer design and the demands of future M-series chips, Apple is likely to implement a redesigned cooling system in the OLED MacBook Pro. This advanced thermal management system will play a crucial role in maintaining optimal operating temperatures, allowing the device to handle the increased heat generated by more powerful processors, such as the anticipated M6 chip.\n\nImproved thermal efficiency is essential for making sure consistent performance and durability. By effectively managing heat, the MacBook Pro will be better equipped to handle resource-intensive tasks like video editing, software development, and 3D rendering. This makes it an ideal choice for professionals who rely on their devices for demanding workloads. Additionally, the enhanced cooling system will contribute to the overall longevity of the device, further solidifying its value as a long-term investment.\n\nPricing and Release Timeline\n\nThe inclusion of OLED technology is expected to result in a slight price increase for the MacBook Pro. Analysts predict that the new models could cost approximately $100-$200 more than their predecessors, reflecting the expense of integrating advanced display components. While this price adjustment may deter some budget-conscious buyers, the improved features and performance are likely to justify the additional cost for most users.\n\nApple is targeting a late 2026 release for the OLED MacBook Pro. Before this launch, the company is expected to release one more iteration of the current design, featuring M5 chips. This timeline provides Apple with the opportunity to refine its OLED technology and ensure a seamless transition for its flagship laptop lineup. By carefully planning this rollout, Apple aims to deliver a product that meets the high expectations of its user base.\n\nDesigned for the Future\n\nThe OLED MacBook Pro is being developed with a forward-thinking approach, making sure it remains competitive and reliable for years to come. Features such as thinner bezels, a streamlined profile, and advanced thermal solutions position the device to support future M-series chips, potentially extending to M10 or M11. This focus on long-term compatibility underscores Apple’s commitment to delivering products that adapt to evolving technological demands.\n\nBy integrating OLED technology and other innovative features, Apple is setting the stage for a new era of MacBook Pro devices. The combination of superior display quality, refined design, and enhanced performance capabilities makes the OLED MacBook Pro a compelling choice for professionals and tech enthusiasts alike. As the late 2026 release date approaches, this device is poised to become a standout addition to Apple’s product lineup.\n\nFind more information on OLED MacBook Pro by browsing our extensive range of articles, guides and tutorials.\n\nSource & Image Credit: Matt Talks Tech\n\n\n\nLatest Geeky Gadgets Deals\n\nSome of our articles include affiliate links. If you buy something through one of these links, Geeky Gadgets may earn an affiliate commission. Learn about our Disclosure Policy"}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-05-07T08:00:00Z", "url": "http://grist.org/global-indigenous-affairs-desk/want-climate-solutions-in-indigenous-territories-better-get-consent/", "publishedAt": "2025-05-07T08:00:00Z", "content": "Four years ago, Harvard University moved a long-planned solar geoengineering project from Arizona to Sápmi, the homelands of Sámi peoples across what is now Norway, Sweden, Finland, and Russia. The S… [+9870 chars]", "title": "Want climate solutions in Indigenous territories? Better get consent.", "fullContent": "Four years ago, Harvard University moved a long-planned solar geoengineering project from Arizona to Sápmi, the homelands of Sámi peoples across what is now Norway, Sweden, Finland, and Russia. The Sámi had no idea it was coming.\n\n“We did not know about the plans until we got alerted by the [Indigenous Environmental Network] and they were saying, ‘You should be aware of this,'” said Sámi council member Åsa Larsson Blind.\n\nReader support makes our work possible. Donate today to keep our site free. All donations DOUBLED! One Time\n\nMonthly $120\n\n$180\n\nOther\n\nDonate $10\n\n$15\n\nOther\n\nDonate\n\nBlind said that it’s unlikely Harvard deliberately ignored consulting the Sámi about the project before moving it to Kiruna, Sweden. More likely, she thinks, they weren’t aware that they needed to.\n\n“But at the same time, you don’t need to do much research to know that Kiruna is in Sápmi, and that there is an Indigenous people,” Blind said. “There is one Indigenous people in Europe, and that’s the Sámi people, and we are not unknown.”\n\nTo support our nonprofit environmental journalism, please consider disabling your ad-blocker to allow ads on Grist. Here's How\n\nThe idea behind solar geoengineering is that it combats global warming by reflecting sun rays back into space with chemical particles sprayed into the atmosphere. Known as the Stratospheric Controlled Perturbation Experiment, or SCoPEx, the Harvard project would have experimented with the dispersal of those chemicals over Sámi lands. But this kind of climate manipulation goes against Sámi traditional beliefs about caring for nature, the Sámi council wrote in an open letter to Harvard that called for an end to the program. Critically, Harvard also failed to inform the Sámi people of the project or obtain their consent before starting it, the council pointed out, violating their right to free, prior, and informed consent — rights enshrined in international law. Representatives with Harvard’s SCoPEx project did not return requests for comment.\n\nThe Sámi are not alone in experiencing such violations and joining the ranks of Indigenous peoples relying on international law to challenge “climate solutions” projects, like SCoPEx, in their territories.\n\nFor the third year running, Indigenous leaders have called for a permanent moratorium on carbon markets, carbon offsets, and geoengineering technologies at the United Nations Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues, or UNPFII. They also demanded an end to all carbon market initiatives within the U.N., like the REDD+, a $5 billion payment scheme that aims to protect forests through private investment in the carbon market. That call, led by the Indigenous Environmental Network, or IEN, and supported by the American Indian Law Alliance, an Indigenous nonprofit, is now bolstered by an IEN report that documents multiple cases where carbon market, carbon offset, and geoengineering projects have violated Indigenous peoples’ rights, and Indigenous people have challenged them. As carbon markets expand into Indigenous homelands, advocates hope these fights for Indigenous rights, in Sápmi and beyond, offer a roadmap to stop a growing industry from exploiting Indigenous peoples.\n\nDepending on how a carbon offset project works to mitigate climate change in design and scale, it generates a certain number of carbon credits — the currency of the carbon market. This allows polluters to offset their emissions by purchasing these credits — governments, businesses, and organizations pay to sequester or remove carbon with things like geoengineering or forest restoration and conservation. Indigenous peoples’ land is often targeted for these efforts, given that they manage or have tenure rights over about 40 percent of the world’s ecologically intact terrestrial landscapes. Because these healthy ecosystems are prime locations for such work, Indigenous peoples living there can quickly become entangled with or impacted by a developing carbon market — often without their knowledge or consent.\n\nTo support our nonprofit environmental journalism, please consider disabling your ad-blocker to allow ads on Grist. Here's How\n\nDuring the United Nations Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues at the United Nations Headquarters in New York. April, 2025. Taily Irvine / Grist\n\nThe IEN report details nine cases of “lawsuits, formal complaints, and public advocacy” where Indigenous peoples, like the Sámi, have invoked the U.N. Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples, known as UNDRIP, to confront and resist initiatives that threaten their lands and well-being.\n\n“I do believe it’s positive that UNDRIP is being used,” Blind said. “Everytime it is cited and it gets recognition, that builds legitimacy. And when we use it boldly and with confidence and we do that together, that builds legitimacy.”\n\nPassed in 2007 by the U.N., UNDRIP contains 46 articles that set the standard for the recognition, protection, and promotion of Indigenous peoples’ rights. The IEN study reveals that more than a third of them have been violated by climate solutions projects. Repeated infringements include a lack of transparency from companies, states, and organizations about the scale of their work, intentionally sowing division within Indigenous communities, increased violence and surveillance of Indigenous peoples, and violations to free, prior, and informed consent.\n\nFor some Indigenous communities, carbon markets present an opportunity to grow their economies and exercise their rights to self determination. And it’s a lucrative industry: The voluntary carbon market saw $16.3 billion in funding by the end of 2024.\n\nFrancesca Hillery, a member of the Round Valley Indian Tribe in California, is partnerships director at the Indigenous Greenhouse Gas Removal Commission, or IGGRC, a collective of Indigenous nations in the U.S. working to mitigate climate change through the carbon market.\n\nHillery said carbon offset projects based in forest or ecosystem restoration often align with Indigenous values and benefit Indigenous communities. But the main benefit to tribes is the financial potential. Tribes in the U.S. need resources to run their governments, Hillery said, and carbon markets may present opportunities for economic growth. In 2015, California’s first forest carbon offset project on Indigenous land was developed on the Round Valley tribe’s land.\n\n“I do understand that there’s this whole critique against the commodification of nature,” Hillery said. “I just think that tribes are looking for solutions for a bunch of different phenomena.”\n\nBut for other Indigenous communities, the expansion of carbon markets raises concerns, especially as some projects have already resulted in Indigenous peoples being evicted from their lands or promised financial compensation that doesn’t materialize. In Peru, for example, the Cordillera Azul National Park was created without the consent of the Kichwa people and other Indigenous communities whose territories it overlaps. Then, the Peruvian government and CIMA, the nonprofit set up to run the park, sold more than 28 million carbon credits for the project. According to IEN, the Peruvian government and CIMA refused to recognize Kichwa land claims while simultaneously profiting from carbon credit sales in the park. In an analysis of reports that detail carbon market impacts, the news outlet Carbon Brief found that more than 70 percent of the reports documented evidence of carbon offset projects harming Indigenous people as well as local communities.\n\nAll of the court cases outlined in the IEN report are of Indigenous people using UNDRIP to fight against carbon markets. But Joanna Cabello, a senior researcher with SOMO, a Netherlands-based organization that investigates multinational corporations and their impacts on people and environments, said rulings in support of Indigenous land rights are still a boon to communities who might welcome carbon projects. The same logic that upholds Indigenous land rights also affords them the right to choose what they want to do with that land, including joining the carbon market.\n\n“The recognition of [Indigenous] rights is always a strong starting point for any type of [carbon market] project, as that would mean that they have the right to say no to the proposal as well as to hold the companies or organizations behind a project accountable,” Cabello said.\n\nCabello has studied carbon offset projects for over 20 years and said that while these markets infringing on Indigenous rights is “not news,” more courts are ruling in favor of Indigenous communities, which isn’t usually the case.\n\nIn 2020, the Kichwa sued the Peruvian government, contesting its refusal to recognize Indigenous territorial rights, the creation of the conservation project on their territory without consent, and the systematic exclusion from making decisions about or receiving financial benefits from carbon credit sales. In 2023 and 2024, the court agreed with the Kichwa, becoming the first judicial rulings in Peru to recognize and uphold Indigenous territorial rights.\n\n“Hopefully, the more and more that communities are able to reach these verdicts, the more that also governments — even if it’s not at the national level, but municipal level or regional level — can start checking who is really benefiting from doing these projects in their territories,” Cabello said. “Hopefully some will side more with Indigenous peoples’ rights.”\n\nThough it’s just one tool, Cabello said using UNDRIP like this shows Indigenous communities that denouncing abuse can be met with meaningful recognition — and tells industries that people are watching their work.\n\nSimilarly, the letter that the Sámi council issued to Harvard demanding an end to SCoPEx clarified the risks and violations associated with such a project. Not only is it required to obtain consent for activities on their lands, Indigenous people have the right, the Sámi council reminded the university, to maintain and strengthen their spiritual relationship to their traditional lands, uphold their responsibilities to future generations, and make decisions about the territories and resources under their stewardship, including air.\n\nAfter continued opposition, Harvard’s solar geoengineering project was terminated in March 2024.\n\n“That’s something, because we don’t have many other examples of a huge institution like Harvard backing down after critique from Indigenous peoples,” Blind said, noting that this issue was successfully addressed outside the court of law.\n\n“It is significant to see that it is actually an option to halt something when you realize that it wasn’t done right.”"}
